                 <height>20</height>
                </size>
               </property>
              </spacer>
             </item>
             <item>
              <widget class="QDoubleSpinBox" name="stereoOutputAmpSpinBox">
               <property name="buttonSymbols">
                <enum>QAbstractSpinBox::NoButtons</enum>
               </property>
               <property name="minimum">
                <double>-24.000000000000000</double>
               </property>
               <property name="maximum">
                <double>24.000000000000000</double>
               </property>
               <property name="singleStep">
                <double>1.000000000000000</double>
               </property>
              </widget>
             </item>
            </layout>
           </item>
           <item>
            <widget class="QSlider" name="stereoOutputAmpSlider">
             <property name="sizePolicy">
              <sizepolicy hsizetype="Minimum" vsizetype="Fixed">
               <horstretch>0</horstretch>
               <verstretch>0</verstretch>
              </sizepolicy>
             </property>
             <property name="toolTip">
              <string>Enables setting the level of the fully mixed stereo output signal.
This is an equivalent of the voltage-controlled amplifier available
in new-gen hardware. However, it's (currently) settable only by
the user and not via the Master Volume control. Together with
the latter, it helps to avoid distortions that may occur in the synth
when using the integer rendering engine.

This control is related to the Output Gain and Reverb Output Gain.
Its value mirrors one of those, whichever is set higher.</string>
             </property>
             <property name="maximum">
              <number>400</number>
             </property>
             <property name="orientation">
              <enum>Qt::Horizontal</enum>
             </property>
             <property name="tickPosition">
              <enum>QSlider::TicksAbove</enum>
             </property>
             <property name="tickInterval">
              <number>100</number>
             </property>
            </widget>
           </item>
           <item>
            <layout class="QHBoxLayout" name="horizontalLayout_4">
             <item>
              <widget class="QCheckBox" name="pinCheckBox">
               <property name="sizePolicy">
                <sizepolicy hsizetype="Fixed" vsizetype="Fixed">
                 <horstretch>0</horstretch>
                 <verstretch>0</verstretch>
                </sizepolicy>
               </property>
               <property name="toolTip">
                <string>Controls how new MIDI connections are handled

When a synth is pinned, all new MIDI connections
are attached to it as its input. When there are none,
the synth remains active and keeps its state, so that
one might e.g. load a SysEx bank and then play
tunes that rely on the timbres defined within. Indeed,
only a single synth may be pinned at a time.

When there is no pinned synth, each new MIDI
connection creates a separate synth initialised
to the default state, and these synths may play
different tunes simultaneously. As soon as the
MIDI source disconnects, the corresponding synth
terminates and no longer consumes resources.</string>
               </property>
               <property name="text">
                <string>Pin Synth</string>
               </property>
              </widget>
             </item>
             <item>
              <widget class="QPushButton" name="synthPropertiesButton">
